WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.904 --> 00:00:06.654
* dramatic music *

2
00:00:06.738 --> 00:00:07.902
I know you.

3
00:00:07.986 --> 00:00:09.415
Not like you're going to.

4
00:00:11.527 --> 00:00:14.014
I got the call from Quiet Ray.
It's time.

5
00:00:14.148 --> 00:00:15.449
[Quiet Ray]
What you're doing now

6
00:00:15.516 --> 00:00:17.251
out in Tulsa.

7
00:00:17.335 --> 00:00:18.904
It's time to share.

8
00:00:21.757 --> 00:00:23.537
[Mitch]
An old girlfriend of mine--

9
00:00:23.621 --> 00:00:25.421
her and her father are having

10
00:00:25.505 --> 00:00:27.621
a problem with their distillery.

11
00:00:27.705 --> 00:00:30.053
It's being strong-armed
by a guy named Dunmire.

12
00:00:30.137 --> 00:00:32.306
That son of a bitch
is the tyrant of Tulsa.

13
00:00:32.390 --> 00:00:33.758
Let me handle him.

14
00:00:33.907 --> 00:00:35.478
[Bevilaqua]
One of your fucking idiots

15
00:00:35.562 --> 00:00:36.578
pulled some weird shit

16
00:00:36.662 --> 00:00:37.847
with my man in
the fucking weed shop.

17
00:00:37.931 --> 00:00:38.917
put a gun in his face.

18
00:00:39.001 --> 00:00:41.003
Because your man
shot his best friend.

19
00:00:43.230 --> 00:00:44.496
You get what you were owed?

20
00:00:44.580 --> 00:00:45.581
That's not the point.

21
00:00:45.665 --> 00:00:46.531
Actually. it is.

22
00:00:46.615 --> 00:00:48.550
But when I shook Dunmire's hand.

23
00:00:48.634 --> 00:00:49.703
I tied my own.

24
00:00:49.787 --> 00:00:51.407
When I partner with someone.

25
00:00:51.491 --> 00:00:53.426
their enemy is my enemy.

26
00:00:53.510 --> 00:00:54.677
So. what do you say?

27
00:00:55.216 --> 00:00:56.984
[Theodore]
Dunmire will react.

28
00:00:57.470 --> 00:00:59.139
-Oh! No! Wait.
-Get in there!

29
00:00:59.223 --> 00:01:00.557
[Theodore screaming]

30
00:01:05.019 --> 00:01:06.521
[car doors close]

31
00:01:06.605 --> 00:01:08.406
It's beyond a bad way to go out.

32
00:01:08.502 --> 00:01:09.503
[car door closes]

33
00:01:09.587 --> 00:01:10.856
* atmospheric music *

34
00:01:10.940 --> 00:01:12.241
[Dwight]
You think this punk

35
00:01:12.325 --> 00:01:15.128
had something
to do with this. alone?

36
00:01:15.643 --> 00:01:17.878
What the fuck was his name?

37
00:01:17.962 --> 00:01:19.356
Cole?

38
00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:20.876
Yeah. Cole.

39
00:01:20.960 --> 00:01:22.494
I don't know.

40
00:01:22.983 --> 00:01:25.386
But I do know
that boy don't take a piss

41
00:01:25.453 --> 00:01:28.689
without his daddy
telling him whose lawn.

42
00:01:28.756 --> 00:01:31.125
Man. I've made
some threats in my life.

43
00:01:31.259 --> 00:01:33.694
like "I'll burn your house down
with you in it."

44
00:01:33.761 --> 00:01:35.772
but it was just idle bullshit.

45
00:01:35.856 --> 00:01:38.092
This is sick.

46
00:01:38.176 --> 00:01:41.079
Dixie Mafia boys
don't fuck around.

47
00:01:44.972 --> 00:01:47.541
Like we do?

48
00:01:48.776 --> 00:01:51.545
* percussive. upbeat music *

49
00:02:18.806 --> 00:02:22.009
***

50
00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:42.329
***

51
00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:55.949
-[organ music playing]
-[quiet chatter]

52
00:03:10.408 --> 00:03:11.775
[Goodie]
Excuse me.

53
00:03:11.859 --> 00:03:13.394
Pardon me. Excuse me.

54
00:03:13.527 --> 00:03:15.496
Excuse me. Pardon me.

55
00:03:15.596 --> 00:03:17.174
-Hey. sorry I'm late.
-Good...

56
00:03:17.258 --> 00:03:18.849
-What the hell is that?
-Eh...

57
00:03:18.933 --> 00:03:21.230
-That's a horseshoe.
-I know it's a horseshoe.

58
00:03:21.314 --> 00:03:22.815
He wasn't a fucking jockey.
you idiot.

59
00:03:22.899 --> 00:03:24.171
They're running
the Georgia Classic.

60
00:03:24.272 --> 00:03:25.506
This is all they had.

61
00:03:26.067 --> 00:03:28.069
A-And listen. uh.
not to change the subject.

62
00:03:28.153 --> 00:03:30.055
but. uh. we got a problem.

63
00:03:31.412 --> 00:03:33.081
Armand's gone on a fucking tear.

64
00:03:33.165 --> 00:03:35.700
doing amends
with that AA bullshit.

65
00:03:35.982 --> 00:03:38.352
And that little backstabbing
weasel talking amends

66
00:03:38.436 --> 00:03:40.338
is him talking about shit
he shouldn't.

67
00:03:40.422 --> 00:03:42.889
And I'm telling you. if New York
hears about the distillery--

68
00:03:42.973 --> 00:03:45.210
Enough with the New York.
Where's Armand now?

69
00:03:45.294 --> 00:03:47.029
Radio silence.
Little shit's gone off the grid.

70
00:03:47.113 --> 00:03:48.514
Well. you can't have him
stringing along.

71
00:03:48.598 --> 00:03:50.377
-You got to pick him up.
-Of course.

72
00:03:50.461 --> 00:03:51.862
What were you thinking?
Seriously?

73
00:03:51.946 --> 00:03:53.514
Why don't you take this outside
and bury it?

74
00:03:53.598 --> 00:03:55.366
-[grunts]
-It's embarrassing. man.

75
00:03:55.450 --> 00:03:56.451
It could've been pink.

76
00:03:56.535 --> 00:03:57.735
You don't feel foolish?

77
00:03:57.858 --> 00:03:59.793
A little bit.

78
00:04:04.431 --> 00:04:06.166
[Dwight]
Margaret.

79
00:04:06.380 --> 00:04:08.248
You look beautiful.

80
00:04:08.382 --> 00:04:10.083
And of course.
you do. too. Joanne.

81
00:04:10.167 --> 00:04:11.735
Yeah. Yep. yep.

82
00:04:11.819 --> 00:04:14.021
There's a big crowd here.
I didn't expect that.

83
00:04:14.254 --> 00:04:16.765
Mm. well. Montague was popular.

84
00:04:16.849 --> 00:04:19.284
Family goes way back.
Generations.

85
00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:23.263
Shall we pay our respects?

86
00:04:25.699 --> 00:04:27.267
[sighs]

87
00:04:28.228 --> 00:04:30.430
-What?
-It's just that ever since

88
00:04:30.514 --> 00:04:34.150
I saw my brother in the box.
it's hard for me to get close.

89
00:04:34.836 --> 00:04:37.304
Maybe it's subconscious.
[chuckles]

90
00:04:37.457 --> 00:04:39.059
I get it.

91
00:04:41.074 --> 00:04:43.210
Shit. Dunmire.

92
00:04:43.791 --> 00:04:46.060
* suspenseful music *

93
00:04:46.267 --> 00:04:48.835
The balls on this guy.

94
00:05:02.346 --> 00:05:04.964
Tough way to go out.

95
00:05:05.048 --> 00:05:06.916
It hurts
just to burn your finger.

96
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:09.202
Imagine your whole body.

97
00:05:10.164 --> 00:05:11.698
Manfredi. right?

98
00:05:11.782 --> 00:05:13.017
You know me?

99
00:05:13.101 --> 00:05:15.636
Yes. I know who you are.

100
00:05:16.403 --> 00:05:19.606
And I concur.
It is a genuine tragedy.

101
00:05:20.153 --> 00:05:23.591
I heard you and their family
were pretty tight.

102
00:05:23.657 --> 00:05:24.871
Close.

103
00:05:24.955 --> 00:05:26.891
That's not your concern.

104
00:05:26.975 --> 00:05:28.543
No. but you are.

105
00:05:30.191 --> 00:05:33.427
I'm not the type of man
that you want to fuck with.

106
00:05:33.511 --> 00:05:35.947
We have that in common.

107
00:05:36.483 --> 00:05:38.650
And if you think
you're gonna do to me

108
00:05:38.734 --> 00:05:40.903
what you did
to your friend over there.

109
00:05:40.987 --> 00:05:42.755
it's gonna be really

110
00:05:42.839 --> 00:05:44.941
fucking difficult.

111
00:05:45.025 --> 00:05:45.867
[laughs softly]

112
00:05:45.951 --> 00:05:47.786
That's slanderous talk. Dwight.

113
00:05:47.870 --> 00:05:50.040
Unless it isn't.

114
00:05:51.271 --> 00:05:52.572
Now. what's stopping me

115
00:05:52.656 --> 00:05:54.991
from shutting
that distillery down again?

116
00:05:55.355 --> 00:05:59.159
So. I'm gonna make you an offer.

117
00:05:59.226 --> 00:06:00.661
take it off your hands.

118
00:06:00.761 --> 00:06:02.896
-Not interested.
-I'll give you three times

119
00:06:02.996 --> 00:06:04.832
what you paid that dead man.

120
00:06:04.932 --> 00:06:07.100
Three times?

121
00:06:08.736 --> 00:06:12.773
Still... not interested.

122
00:06:13.707 --> 00:06:17.244
This business requires
sound judgement.

123
00:06:18.211 --> 00:06:21.381
Not the foul hand
of a bottom-feeder.

124
00:06:22.850 --> 00:06:25.719
You ain't no distiller.
Manfredi.

125
00:06:27.054 --> 00:06:28.589
[Cleo]
What are you doing here?

126
00:06:28.689 --> 00:06:30.858
* tense music *

127
00:06:30.957 --> 00:06:33.527
-Get out of here. Leave!
-[people gasping]

128
00:06:33.594 --> 00:06:35.095
I know it was you. you bastard!

129
00:06:35.195 --> 00:06:36.363
I know you don't
mean that. darling.

130
00:06:36.430 --> 00:06:37.431
Hey.

131
00:06:37.565 --> 00:06:39.667
Don't fucking touch her.

132
00:06:47.675 --> 00:06:49.909
That'll cost you. cowboy.

133
00:06:51.912 --> 00:06:53.747
Let's go.

134
00:07:01.689 --> 00:07:03.390
Oh. You want me to do that?

135
00:07:03.491 --> 00:07:05.125
I know how to do this.

136
00:07:05.225 --> 00:07:07.561
-Oh. yeah? All right. Okay.
-Yeah.

137
00:07:07.628 --> 00:07:10.397
Cigar at eight o'clock
in the morning?

138
00:07:10.464 --> 00:07:11.832
Hey.

139
00:07:11.932 --> 00:07:14.735
Did you get the goods
on Dunmire?

140
00:07:14.802 --> 00:07:15.969
Yeah. I was up all night.

141
00:07:16.069 --> 00:07:18.371
I found the title
for the distillery.

142
00:07:18.438 --> 00:07:20.140
-Yeah? And the P&Ls?
-Yeah.

143
00:07:20.240 --> 00:07:22.776
This guy hasn't made
a profit for ten years.

144
00:07:22.910 --> 00:07:24.645
What about the back stock?

145
00:07:24.778 --> 00:07:27.114
Maybe 100 grand of the 12-year.

146
00:07:27.214 --> 00:07:28.716
Which they couldn't
sell. either. you know?

147
00:07:28.782 --> 00:07:30.117
'Cause there's no distributor.

148
00:07:30.217 --> 00:07:32.486
Did you happen to know
it's illegal

149
00:07:32.620 --> 00:07:34.287
for a distiller to sell direct?

150
00:07:34.421 --> 00:07:35.789
-Yeah. I did know.
-No. you didn't.

151
00:07:35.889 --> 00:07:37.290
-Yeah. I fucking knew.
-No. you didn't. Joanne.

152
00:07:37.390 --> 00:07:39.459
Come on. Alway--
"I always know everything."

153
00:07:39.560 --> 00:07:41.995
-You don't know everything.
-[clears throat]

154
00:07:42.129 --> 00:07:43.597
Well. anyway. we're stuck with

155
00:07:43.664 --> 00:07:45.432
all these cases that we can't
put on the shelves.

156
00:07:45.533 --> 00:07:48.836
plus. a lot of new enemies.
so what's going on?

157
00:07:49.770 --> 00:07:52.940
Maybe we take the money
that Dunmire offered

158
00:07:53.006 --> 00:07:54.107
-Mm.
-and we build

159
00:07:54.207 --> 00:07:55.509
-our own distillery.
-[moaning]

160
00:07:55.609 --> 00:07:58.111
Mm-mmm. No. there's no way.
No way.

161
00:07:58.178 --> 00:08:00.413
I don't have enough time.
I'm too ancient.

162
00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:03.684
Plus. this guy offered me
triple for what I paid

163
00:08:03.784 --> 00:08:05.786
after I insulted
the hell out of him.

164
00:08:05.886 --> 00:08:07.988
so it tells me
it's got to be worth more.

165
00:08:08.088 --> 00:08:10.457
That's what it tells me.
What do you think?

166
00:08:10.524 --> 00:08:13.661
Tells me we should've gone into
the funeral parlor business.

167
00:08:13.794 --> 00:08:15.228
-Funny.
-Coffee?

168
00:08:15.328 --> 00:08:17.297
Why not? Take a shot at it.

169
00:08:17.364 --> 00:08:19.567
* atmospheric music *

170
00:08:23.704 --> 00:08:25.072
[car door opens]

171
00:08:31.945 --> 00:08:34.014
That poor man.

172
00:08:34.147 --> 00:08:36.049
This is tragic.

173
00:08:36.149 --> 00:08:39.086
Yeah. Mitch.
who's the guy in the hat?

174
00:08:40.153 --> 00:08:41.722
Insurance adjuster.

175
00:08:41.855 --> 00:08:43.155
-Mm.
-Said a log

176
00:08:43.256 --> 00:08:44.658
rolled out of the fire.
caught the rug.

177
00:08:44.725 --> 00:08:46.560
-Mm-hmm.
-Human error.

178
00:08:46.694 --> 00:08:48.195
Yeah. give me a break.

179
00:08:48.295 --> 00:08:50.263
Well?

180
00:08:51.431 --> 00:08:52.700
They're not gonna pay.

181
00:08:52.833 --> 00:08:55.068
Dunmire's got the whole county
in his pocket.

182
00:08:55.202 --> 00:08:57.504
Cops. fire inspector.
that asshole.

183
00:08:57.605 --> 00:09:00.473
the goddamn governor. Pathetic.

184
00:09:00.540 --> 00:09:01.975
Yeah. but he couldn't
buy your father.

185
00:09:02.042 --> 00:09:03.410
Look at the results.

186
00:09:03.543 --> 00:09:05.846
Cleo. can I ask you to. like.

187
00:09:05.913 --> 00:09:08.515
dig down. memory-wise?

188
00:09:08.582 --> 00:09:12.419
Dunmire-- I don't think he cared
about buying the distillery.

189
00:09:12.552 --> 00:09:15.555
but he was willing to pay
three times the amount.

190
00:09:15.689 --> 00:09:18.225
which is food for thought.

191
00:09:18.325 --> 00:09:19.827
I'm curious--

192
00:09:19.893 --> 00:09:21.394
I'm just asking--

193
00:09:21.494 --> 00:09:24.131
do you know something
that we don't know?

194
00:09:43.951 --> 00:09:45.185
[Dwight]
Damn.

195
00:09:45.252 --> 00:09:46.954
Whoa.

196
00:09:48.155 --> 00:09:50.991
These ain't bodies.

197
00:09:51.859 --> 00:09:53.393
My dad's 50-year.

198
00:09:53.493 --> 00:09:54.895
Came of age this spring.

199
00:09:54.995 --> 00:09:57.798
50-year-old bourbon
made by a master distiller?

200
00:09:57.931 --> 00:09:58.966
It doesn't get any rarer

201
00:09:59.099 --> 00:10:00.600
-than this.
-[Cleo] Nope.

202
00:10:00.701 --> 00:10:04.071
My father made this
with his father and grandfather.

203
00:10:04.137 --> 00:10:06.573
and this vintage
was the best of the best.

204
00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:08.475
Bit of a legend in these parts.

205
00:10:08.608 --> 00:10:10.377
Dunmire suspected it existed.

206
00:10:10.443 --> 00:10:12.746
just didn't know
where it was stashed.

207
00:10:12.846 --> 00:10:14.748
That's planning ahead.

208
00:10:14.815 --> 00:10:16.616
I only just found out about it
when my dad's lawyer

209
00:10:16.717 --> 00:10:17.751
sent me his will.

210
00:10:17.851 --> 00:10:20.153
You know. a 50-year-old bourbon

211
00:10:20.287 --> 00:10:22.289
can go for five grand a bottle.

212
00:10:22.389 --> 00:10:24.658
What do you say you have
in here. a hundred barrels?

213
00:10:24.792 --> 00:10:26.559
-Two hundred.
-Two hundred?

214
00:10:26.626 --> 00:10:29.462
And there's a 150 bottles
per barrel. so that's...

215
00:10:29.562 --> 00:10:31.999
-Big money.
-$150 million. to be exact.

216
00:10:32.099 --> 00:10:33.500
Holy shit.

217
00:10:33.600 --> 00:10:36.737
Yeah. you can say that again.
$150 million.

218
00:10:36.804 --> 00:10:39.372
* upbeat music *

219
00:10:46.847 --> 00:10:48.782
[Cleo]
Okay.

220
00:10:48.882 --> 00:10:50.650
Here we are.

221
00:10:50.784 --> 00:10:53.353
[coughs]
Uh-huh.

222
00:10:53.486 --> 00:10:55.322
Cooker and fermenter.

223
00:10:56.056 --> 00:10:58.125
That there is the still.

224
00:10:58.225 --> 00:11:01.194
I remember the grain handler
used to be out back.

225
00:11:01.328 --> 00:11:03.430
Lot of fond memories
behind that thing.

226
00:11:03.496 --> 00:11:05.933
I suggest shutting up. Mitch.

227
00:11:05.999 --> 00:11:07.935
Good idea. Mitch.

228
00:11:09.136 --> 00:11:10.938
And this is where
the magic happens.

229
00:11:11.004 --> 00:11:13.106
Well. happened.

230
00:11:13.173 --> 00:11:14.875
Uh. broken conveyor.

231
00:11:14.975 --> 00:11:17.845
I don't know
what half that junk is.

232
00:11:18.645 --> 00:11:20.480
These are the bottling lines.

233
00:11:20.547 --> 00:11:22.282
[Mitch]
Well. what used to be

234
00:11:22.349 --> 00:11:25.018
the bottling lines. damn rats.

235
00:11:25.118 --> 00:11:27.020
Shuttered distillery 101:

236
00:11:27.120 --> 00:11:30.557
barrels to bungholes
to not bottling.

237
00:11:30.690 --> 00:11:31.992
[Grace]
Bungholes?

238
00:11:32.059 --> 00:11:34.795
-That sounds dirty.
-Did you say "bunghole"?

239
00:11:34.862 --> 00:11:36.363
Boss don't like
the word "bunghole."

240
00:11:36.496 --> 00:11:37.731
I don't like
the word "bunghole."

241
00:11:37.865 --> 00:11:40.000
You got ladies here.
A little respect.

242
00:11:40.100 --> 00:11:43.503
A bunghole
is a circular incision bored

243
00:11:43.570 --> 00:11:47.240
into a sealed barrel to allow
for the release of its contents.

244
00:11:47.374 --> 00:11:48.742
That's all. Moving on.

245
00:11:50.177 --> 00:11:51.478
Dwight. look.

246
00:11:51.544 --> 00:11:54.114
Weed is up tenfold.
and the casino twice that.

247
00:11:54.214 --> 00:11:57.084
Do we really need
some mold-infested firetrap?

248
00:11:57.184 --> 00:11:58.318
There's history here.

249
00:11:58.385 --> 00:11:59.552
This is where
it all started. Bodhi.

250
00:11:59.652 --> 00:12:02.555
You know.
you got booze. moonshine.

251
00:12:02.689 --> 00:12:04.457
most likely started
by the Italians.

252
00:12:04.557 --> 00:12:05.893
[Bodhi]
The hard stuff.

253
00:12:06.026 --> 00:12:08.395
wasn't that English.
Scottish. Irish?

254
00:12:08.495 --> 00:12:10.898
The Italians
brought breadsticks.

255
00:12:11.031 --> 00:12:12.732
-[chuckles]
-[Tyson] I just don't get it.

256
00:12:12.866 --> 00:12:15.702
If it was so profitable.
why-why did it go broke?

257
00:12:15.803 --> 00:12:17.838
[Cleo]
Dunmire killed the competition.

258
00:12:17.905 --> 00:12:20.440
made sure every other
distributor wouldn't touch us.

